# 39_objects_set_stroke_cap_join — closes the appearance branch's
# enum-token sub-axis.
#
# s239 m1 + m2 shipped the colour-and-thickness axis (set_fill,
# set_stroke, set_stroke_width). s240 m1 ships the paired enum-
# token verbs that round out stroke's vocabulary: cap and join.
# Both are fields on StrokeStyle (SceneNode.hpp:76-77) — three-
# value enums surfaced as lowercase string tokens:
#
#   LineCap  : "butt" / "round" / "square"
#   LineJoin : "miter" / "round" / "bevel"
#
# These match SVG's stroke-linecap / stroke-linejoin attribute
# conventions exactly; no translation table needed at the export
# seam. Same posture as StylesScriptable::stroke_cap / stroke_join
# (s225 m1) — that's also where the decode_cap / decode_join /
# cap_to_string / join_to_string helpers come from, lifted in
# shape into ObjectsScriptable's anon namespace this session.
#
# Material differences from set_stroke_width (m2):
#   - Enum token args, not numeric. The anon namespace gains four
#     helpers (two pump-pair pairs): decode_cap + cap_to_string
#     for LineCap, decode_join + join_to_string for LineJoin.
#     Encode + decode live next to each other in the same file
#     (Unix-pump convention). Two callers of this shape now
#     (StylesScriptable + ObjectsScriptable); three would justify
#     a lift to curvz_utils. Logged as backlog this session.
#   - Unknown-token policy: SILENT NO-OP, not a degrade to a
#     safe default. set_fill / set_stroke degrade unknown colour
#     tokens to CurrentColor (a documented safe default for
#     paint). Cap / join have no equivalent safe default — there's
#     no "default cap" the way CurrentColor is a default paint —
#     so an unknown cap or join token is a silent no-op and the
#     model state stays where it was. Matches
#     StylesScriptable::stroke_cap's posture exactly. Phase 8
#     exercises this specifically.
#   - Partial binding-clear: clears bound_style (a cap or join
#     edit is a direct appearance edit that breaks the style
#     binding), preserves both fill_swatch_id and stroke_swatch_id
#     (swatch bindings represent paint references; cap/join
#     edits don't touch paint, so neither swatch binding is
#     disturbed). Same convention set_stroke_width established.
#   - Universal across SceneNode subtypes. cap and join are
#     fields on StrokeStyle, which every SceneNode has. Group /
#     Compound / etc. accept the verb without refusal.
#
# Verify-before-assume's SEVENTH and EIGHTH "fits unmodified"
# cases in a row. EditAppearanceCommand's whole-StrokeStyle
# capture covers cap and join along with paint / width / miter /
# opacity without modification. Three sessions in a row
# (s238 / s239 / s240) of "the command we have already fits the
# next verb at the same seam" — the verify-before-assume tail
# observation has now landed five applications (set_fill at
# s238 m1, set_stroke at s239 m1, set_stroke_width at s239 m2,
# set_stroke_cap and set_stroke_join at s240 m1).
#
# ── Owns-its-conditions structure (CANON) ────────────────────────────────
#
# BUILD UP / VALIDATE / TEAR DOWN. The smoke mints its own test
# layer and three test objects (a Path `p` for the cap/join
# matrix, a Group `g` for the universal-class probe, a second
# Path `v` for the visual-close phase), validates the new surface
# end-to-end, and tears everything back down. Net structural
# change to the doc: zero. Side effects on the undo stack:
# AddNodeCommand entries for the mints, EditPathCommand for
# geometry sets, EditAppearanceCommand entries for the cap / join
# / fill / stroke / stroke_width calls, DeleteObjectCommand pairs
# for the teardown.
#
# ── Pre-stated count ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Expected: 16 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#
# Breakdown:
#   Phase 1 (REGISTRY):                                       → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 2 (DISPATCH — baseline count):                      → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 3 (BUILD UP — mint test_layer, mint `p` as Path,
#            geometry, baseline cap and join defaults):
#     p type == "path"                                         → 1 assert.
#     p cap == "butt"  (LineCap::Butt struct default)          → 1 assert.
#     p join == "miter" (LineJoin::Miter struct default)       → 1 assert.
#   Phase 4 (SET cap "round"):
#     p cap == "round"                                         → 1 assert.
#   Phase 5 (SET cap "square"):
#     p cap == "square"                                        → 1 assert.
#   Phase 6 (SET join "round"):
#     p join == "round"                                        → 1 assert.
#   Phase 7 (SET join "bevel"):
#     p join == "bevel"                                        → 1 assert.
#   Phase 8 (UNKNOWN-TOKEN SILENT NO-OP — cap stays "square"
#            from Phase 5):
#     p cap == "square"                                        → 1 assert.
#   Phase 9 (UNIVERSAL — cap and join on a Group are NOT refused):
#     g type == "group",
#     g cap == "round",
#     g join == "bevel"                                        → 3 asserts.
#   Phase 10 (VISUAL CLOSE — fat stroke with cap=round and
#             join=round on a polygon `v`; visible blue outline
#             with bulging ends and bevelled corners):
#     v stroke_width == 40.0,
#     v cap == "round",
#     v join == "round"                                        → 3 asserts.
#   Phase 11 (CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "path" still resolves):
#     found_path type == "path"                                → 1 assert.
#   Phase 12 (TEAR DOWN — round-trip count):
#     objects count == count_before                            → 1 assert.
#
# Total: 0 + 0 + 3 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 3 + 3 + 1 + 1 = 16.
#
# ── On the unknown-token Phase 8 ─────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Phase 8 calls `set_stroke_cap "trapezoidal"` — a deliberately
# nonsense token. The decode_cap helper returns std::nullopt;
# the verb's early-return clause hits before any command push,
# so the model state stays exactly where Phase 5 left it
# (cap == "square"). The trace assert verifies the no-op
# behaviour directly. This is the key behavioural difference
# from set_fill / set_stroke (which would degrade an unknown
# token to CurrentColor); the divergence is documented at the
# verb body and at the file header.
#
# Why no equivalent unknown-token phase for join: the divergence
# is exactly parallel to cap; one assertion covers the class.
# A future expansion of the smoke could add `set_stroke_join
# "octagonal"` symmetrically — the count would go to 17, the
# new behaviour confirmed would be identical. Holding to one
# unknown-token assertion this milestone for parsimony.
#
# ── On the visual-close Phase 10 ─────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This is the milestone's payoff phase. The smoke mints a
# second path `v` (separate from `p` to keep the cap/join
# matrix on `p` clean), sets its geometry to a 200x200 square,
# layers all the appearance values needed for the visual to
# read: fill=none (transparent interior so the corners are
# clearly visible), stroke=blue (the outline colour), stroke_width
# = 40.0 (fat enough for cap and join effects to register at
# default zoom — recall Scott's "4px reads as a hairline"
# observation from s239 m2), cap = "round" (bulging stroke
# ends), join = "round" (smooth bevelled corners).
#
# The trace asserts the three new fields independently; the
# VISUAL channel is "Scott looks at the canvas and sees a
# 200x200 square outlined in fat blue stroke with rounded
# corners." Three-channel acceptance for the milestone hinges
# on this phase's visual behaviour. If the trace passes but the
# corners render as sharp miters (or the ends render as flat
# butts), the milestone has not landed.
#
# Three-channel acceptance for s240 m1 = trace pass (16 asserts)
# + clean build + VISIBLE rounded-corner rounded-end fat outline
# after Phase 10.
#
# ── Canvas-observable (three-channel acceptance) ─────────────────────────
#
# Trace channel: the 16 asserts above.
# Visual channel: AFTER Phase 10, the document shows a 200x200
#   square at user-origin (300, 0) with NO fill, a 40-pixel BLUE
#   outline, ROUNDED corners (no sharp angles) and ROUNDED stroke
#   ends. Visually distinct from the s239 m2 visual-close shape
#   (which had sharp miter corners and flat butt ends).
# Build channel: Scott's compile.

#[sub] === Phase 1: REGISTRY ===
#[sub] `objects` should appear in the registry list — baseline.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: DISPATCH — baseline count ===
#[sub] Captures the pre-mint object count to compare against after
#[sub] teardown.

get objects count
set count_before to result

#[sub] === Phase 3: BUILD UP — mint test layer, Path, geometry ===
#[sub] Mint a sentinel-named test layer, activate it, mint `p` as a
#[sub] Path, set its geometry. A freshly-minted Path has
#[sub] stroke.cap defaulting to LineCap::Butt and stroke.join
#[sub] defaulting to LineJoin::Miter (SceneNode.hpp:76-77 struct
#[sub] defaults). The baseline queries return "butt" and "miter"
#[sub] before any set_stroke_cap / set_stroke_join call.

layers new
set test_layer to result
layers.test_layer rename "objects_set_stroke_cap_join_smoke_s240_m1"
layers.test_layer activate

objects new "path"
set p to result
objects.p set_path_data "M 0 0 L 100 0 L 100 100 L 0 100 Z"

assert objects.p type == "path"
assert objects.p cap == "butt"
assert objects.p join == "miter"

#[sub] === Phase 4: SET cap "round" ===
#[sub] decode_cap("round") returns LineCap::Round; the verb writes
#[sub] node->stroke.cap = Round, pushes EditAppearanceCommand with
#[sub] whole-StrokeStyle before/after (only cap differs). The
#[sub] cap_to_string helper round-trips the enum back through the
#[sub] query.

objects.p set_stroke_cap "round"
assert objects.p cap == "round"

#[sub] === Phase 5: SET cap "square" ===
#[sub] Third vocabulary value. The smoke sweeps the three-token
#[sub] vocabulary at cap (butt baseline in Phase 3, round in
#[sub] Phase 4, square here). join's three-token sweep follows in
#[sub] Phases 6-7 — only two phases there because the baseline
#[sub] (miter) was already asserted in Phase 3.

objects.p set_stroke_cap "square"
assert objects.p cap == "square"

#[sub] === Phase 6: SET join "round" ===
#[sub] decode_join("round") returns LineJoin::Round. Note: the
#[sub] string "round" is valid vocabulary for BOTH cap and join —
#[sub] LineCap and LineJoin happen to overlap on that one token.
#[sub] decode_cap and decode_join are SEPARATE helpers that don't
#[sub] share state; "round" maps to LineCap::Round on the cap
#[sub] side and LineJoin::Round on the join side. Two enums, same
#[sub] string, different values.

objects.p set_stroke_join "round"
assert objects.p join == "round"

#[sub] === Phase 7: SET join "bevel" ===
#[sub] Third vocabulary value at the join axis. "bevel" is unique
#[sub] to LineJoin (not a LineCap value), so this token also
#[sub] verifies that set_stroke_cap "bevel" would be a no-op (the
#[sub] vocabularies don't cross-contaminate). A direct assertion
#[sub] for the cross-contamination case is not in this smoke; the
#[sub] guarantee comes from decode_cap's switch statement only
#[sub] mapping "butt" / "round" / "square".

objects.p set_stroke_join "bevel"
assert objects.p join == "bevel"

#[sub] === Phase 8: UNKNOWN-TOKEN SILENT NO-OP ===
#[sub] `set_stroke_cap "trapezoidal"` is a deliberately nonsense
#[sub] token. decode_cap returns std::nullopt; the verb's
#[sub] early-return clause hits before any command push. The
#[sub] model state stays at what Phase 5 left it: cap == "square".
#[sub] No command on the undo stack, no notify_doc_changed.
#[sub]
#[sub] Key behavioural divergence from set_fill / set_stroke:
#[sub] those degrade unknown tokens to CurrentColor (a documented
#[sub] safe-default for paint). Cap and join have no equivalent
#[sub] safe-default — there is no "default cap" the way CurrentColor
#[sub] is a default paint. So the silent-no-op posture is the
#[sub] correct read, matching StylesScriptable::stroke_cap's
#[sub] convention.

objects.p set_stroke_cap "trapezoidal"
assert objects.p cap == "square"

#[sub] === Phase 9: UNIVERSAL — cap and join on a Group are NOT refused ===
#[sub] Same universal posture as set_fill / set_stroke /
#[sub] set_stroke_width. Appearance lives on every SceneNode
#[sub] subtype, including container types that don't draw a
#[sub] stroked region directly. The model field update lands;
#[sub] the visual effect on the Group depends on the container's
#[sub] render path (style inheritance / per-child effects).

objects new "group"
set g to result
objects.g set_stroke_cap "round"
objects.g set_stroke_join "bevel"

assert objects.g type == "group"
assert objects.g cap == "round"
assert objects.g join == "bevel"

#[sub] === Phase 10: VISUAL CLOSE ===
#[sub] The appearance branch's enum-token sub-axis payoff phase.
#[sub] Mint a second Path `v`, set its geometry to a 200x200
#[sub] square offset to user-origin (300, 0) so it doesn't overlap
#[sub] the layout of any earlier test object. Layer the appearance
#[sub] values needed for the visual to read clearly:
#[sub]   - fill = "none" (transparent interior; corners visible
#[sub]     without competing fill colour).
#[sub]   - stroke = "blue" (clear outline colour).
#[sub]   - stroke_width = 40.0 (fat enough for cap and join
#[sub]     effects to register at default zoom; recall Scott's
#[sub]     "4px reads as a hairline" observation from s239 m2).
#[sub]   - cap = "round" (bulging stroke ends — though closed
#[sub]     paths don't have ends in the geometric sense, the
#[sub]     setting is still observable on the model).
#[sub]   - join = "round" (smooth bevelled corners — the dominant
#[sub]     visual cue, since a closed square has four corners).
#[sub] The trace asserts the three new fields independently; the
#[sub] VISUAL channel — Scott looking at the canvas — shows a
#[sub] 200x200 blue-outlined square with rounded corners.

objects new "path"
set v to result
objects.v set_path_data "M 300 0 L 500 0 L 500 200 L 300 200 Z"
objects.v set_fill "none"
objects.v set_stroke "blue"
objects.v set_stroke_width 40.0
objects.v set_stroke_cap "round"
objects.v set_stroke_join "round"

assert objects.v stroke_width == 40.0
assert objects.v cap == "round"
assert objects.v join == "round"

#[sub] === Phase 11: CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "path" still resolves ===
#[sub] Sanity check that the appearance work didn't disturb the iid
#[sub] index. Same shape smokes 36 / 37 / 38 used. `p` and `v` are
#[sub] both Paths; first-hit returns one of them.

objects find_by_type "path"
set found_path to result
assert objects.found_path type == "path"

#[sub] === Phase 12: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Four mints (test_layer, p, g, v) — four matching deletes.
#[sub] count returns to count_before — round-trip baseline.

objects delete p
objects delete g
objects delete v
layers delete test_layer

get objects count
assert objects count == count_before

#[sub] === Final list — registry sanity ===
#[sub] `objects` still present; no transient proxies registered.

list

#[sub] Done. The s240 m1 surface is validated:
#[sub]   - `objects.<iid> set_stroke_cap "<token>"` accepts the
#[sub]     LineCap vocabulary ("butt" / "round" / "square"), writes
#[sub]     the value directly onto SceneNode::stroke.cap, clears
#[sub]     bound_style (style binding break), preserves
#[sub]     fill_swatch_id and stroke_swatch_id (paint bindings
#[sub]     don't disturb on a cap edit), pushes EditAppearanceCommand
#[sub]     with whole-StrokeStyle before/after (only cap differs).
#[sub]   - `objects.<iid> set_stroke_join "<token>"` accepts the
#[sub]     LineJoin vocabulary ("miter" / "round" / "bevel"); same
#[sub]     shape and binding-clear convention as set_stroke_cap.
#[sub]   - `cap` and `join` queries return text tokens via the
#[sub]     cap_to_string / join_to_string anon-namespace helpers.
#[sub]   - Unknown token = silent no-op (NOT CurrentColor-degrade).
#[sub]   - Universal across SceneNode subtypes.
#[sub]   - The canvas-observable arc's appearance branch closes
#[sub]     its enum-token sub-axis. With s239 m1 + m2 (colour and
#[sub]     thickness) and s240 m1 (cap and join), the stroke axis
#[sub]     is addressable from scripts on four of its six fields;
#[sub]     remaining miter / opacity are numeric and reuse
#[sub]     arg_as_double from s239 m2 — scheduled for s241.
#[sub]
#[sub] Pre-stated: 16 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#[sub]
#[sub] What's still NOT covered by s240 m1 (and that's by design):
#[sub]   - stroke_miter and stroke_opacity verbs. Both numeric,
#[sub]     both reuse arg_as_double; scheduled for s241.
#[sub]   - Gradient tokens on fill or stroke. Same scope-limit as
#[sub]     s238 / s239.
#[sub]   - Swatch / style binding via script. Same scope-limit.
#[sub]   - Whether to align script-side binding-clear with
#[sub]     mutate_appearance's broader convention (both swatch
#[sub]     bindings cleared on ANY appearance edit) — backlog
#[sub]     item carried over from s239 m2.
#[sub]   - Promotion of decode_cap / cap_to_string / decode_join /
#[sub]     join_to_string from anon-namespace duplication
#[sub]     (StylesScriptable + ObjectsScriptable) to a curvz_utils
#[sub]     pump pair. Two callers is duplication, not yet a
#[sub]     pattern; three is the threshold. Backlog item this
#[sub]     session.
#[sub]   - Undo / redo exercise. Three-channel acceptance for
#[sub]     Scott visually after Phase 10.
